{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619009"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:26:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:26:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16520"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16520"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.68,0.1,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9211"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75403"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9211"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16520"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60913"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8512"},{"type":"tags","id":"10260"},{"type":"tags","id":"10271"},{"type":"tags","id":"10317"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21844"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21849"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75403"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELower motor neurons in the ventral horn of the spinal cord control skeletal muscle contraction. Each lower motor neuron forms synapses with multiple muscle fibres, creating a functional unit for force generation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the organisation and function of lower motor neurons?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A motor unit consists of one lower motor neuron and one muscle fibre","A motor unit consists of one lower motor neuron and all its innervated muscle fibres","A motor unit consists of multiple lower motor neurons and one muscle fibre","A motor unit consists of multiple lower motor neurons and multiple muscle fibres","A motor unit consists of one lower motor neuron and muscle fibres from different muscles"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe basic functional unit of motor control is \u003Cstrong\u003Ea motor unit consisting of one lower motor neuron and all its innervated muscle fibres\u003C/strong\u003E. This arrangement allows for precise control of muscle contraction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding why the other options are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA motor unit consists of one lower motor neuron and one muscle fibre\u003C/strong\u003E - Lower motor neurons branch to innervate multiple muscle fibres, enabling coordinated contraction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA motor unit consists of multiple lower motor neurons and one muscle fibre\u003C/strong\u003E - Multiple innervation would prevent precise control and could lead to uncoordinated contraction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA motor unit consists of multiple lower motor neurons and multiple muscle fibres\u003C/strong\u003E - This arrangement would make selective activation of specific muscle regions impossible\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA motor unit consists of one lower motor neuron and muscle fibres from different muscles\u003C/strong\u003E - Each motor unit is confined to a single muscle to maintain functional specificity\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMotor unit size varies according to functional requirements. Fine movements use small motor units (few muscle fibres), while powerful movements employ large motor units (many muscle fibres). This organisation optimises both precision and strength.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A motor unit consists of a single lower motor neuron and all the muscle fibres it innervates","Lower motor neurons control muscle force through both recruitment of additional motor units and rate coding","The size principle dictates that smaller motor units are recruited before larger ones during force generation"],"references":["Javed K, Daly DT. Neuroanatomy, Lower Motor Neuron Lesion. 2023 Aug 14. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30969636.","Garg N, Park SB, Vucic S, Yiannikas C, Spies J, Howells J, Huynh W, Matamala JM, Krishnan AV, Pollard JD, Cornblath DR, Reilly MM, Kiernan MC. Differentiating lower motor neuron syndromes. J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry. 2017 Jun;88(6):474-483. doi: 10.1136/jnnp-2016-313526. Epub 2016 Dec 21. PMID: 28003344; PMCID: PMC5529975.","Ravits J, Stack J. The lower motor neuron homunculus. Brain. 2022 Nov 21;145(11):3727-3729. doi: 10.1093/brain/awac310. Erratum in: Brain. 2023 Feb 13;146(2):e12. doi: 10.1093/brain/awac383. PMID: 36029046; PMCID: PMC9679163.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60913"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16520"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60913"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T19:30:43+10:30","up